We usually use 3d printed covers. This year, we‚Äôre using this one:

Introducing the Nifty Bot Breaker Shroud! General Forum
I finally got around to tidying up and uploading the main breaker shroud that I designed during DCMP this year! Here is the prototype mounted on 2412‚Äôs robot Crane: [Breaker] I modified the design slightly to allow both cables to come out the sides, and to improve printing without support. I also made versions for all 3 possible wire orientations: [Breaker Options] Check it out and download here: TheNiftyBot.com - Breaker Shroud

It fully covers the wires and prevents falling game pieces (coral) from accidentally hitting the off button.

IMG_02401920√ó1764 295 KB

Definitely would recommend this.

At least two years, 3946 used ‚Äúliquid electrical tape‚Äù for main breaker and new/re-done battery connections. Here‚Äôs an example in black:

amazon.com

Amazon.com: STAR BRITE Liquid Electrical Tape - Black - 32 OZ (084134) :...

Introducing STAR BRITE Liquid Electrical Tape 32 Ounce, also available in both 4-ounce cans and 1-ounce tubes, designed to meet all your electrical sealing needs. Superior to electrical tape, it adheres to metal, plastic, vinyl, rubber, and composite...

Our electrical lead mentor purchased a can of red and a can of black. By year three or four it gummed up, so only buy 1 or 2 years‚Äô worth at a time.
Note: this is something you want to apply outdoors, under a chemical hood, or other nearly as powerful air circulation from outdoors to outdoors. In our case, we applied this outdoors, usually under covered walkways and landings because precipitation is possible most days. Here in Southeast Louisiana, we always had a reasonable number of days with outdoor temperatures suitable for curing during build season. YMMV mostly by latitude.
